title: La Femme Chauve-Souris • Enamel Pin
description:
1.3" x 1.76" Soft Enamel Pin Single Posted Rubber Clasp Inspired by "La Femme Chauve-Souris" by Albert Joseph Pénot A French painter known for his depictions of the female nude, Albert Joseph Pénot (1862-1930) was often inspired by the macabre and sinister.

 One of his darker works, "La Femme Chauve-Souris" (c. 1890), also known as "Bat Woman," features a beautiful naked woman floating against an ambiguous cloudy sky, marked as occult by the large bat wings emerging from her back. Her sumptuous form is brightly lit from above, yet her intense stare out at the viewer is unnaturally lit from below, blurring the line between attraction and fear.

 While not considered a part of the art historical canon, the painting has a cult following, inspiring replication on prints, apparel, and more. Comes packaged with Pin Museum branded backer card, and a protective polybag.

This item is made by Pin Museum. It ships from our US warehouse.

title: Alternative Fashion not Alternative Facts Pin
description:
Grab the Alternative Fashion not Alternative Facts Pin from Puvithel! Part of the purchase of this pin goes to a charity organization! See below for more details.

  • 1.5" x 2" 
  • glow in the dark text
  • These pins are made in the USA.
  • 50% of proceeds will go to organizations that fund scientific research in the areas of green energy and conservation.

Puvithel Says: "Currently I am donating to the American Association for the Advancement of Science and the Nature Conservancy. I am open to suggestions as well if you know of a deserving fund. I would also be happy to answer questions or concerns you may have about nuclear power, green energy, and climate change and why I feel so strongly about it via PM. Please do not ask me about any political items that are not related to these topics :)

If you'd like to aid in supporting, please consider directly donating to funds/charities that support these causes, or buy a pin!

While I try to keep out of politics, I am an aspiring punk designer, and I feel an important part of punk is fighting for a better world.

As some of you know, I am only a part-time artist. By day I work as a nuclear engineer. I am a strong proponent of green energy, and I'm proud that I have a job that helps reduce green house emissions by facilitating correct data measurement in nuclear power plant facilities.

I'm also proud to be an American, but recently the US government has been scaring me with its disregard for data. This is not about party lines. I do not claim to know what is best for our country, I am neither a law maker nor a politician. But I do know that it is important to have accurate, scientific data to support whatever policy decisions are made.

The reprimands I would face if I falsified data on a report are significant. The quality assurance reprimands for even accidental, minor errors are significant. Our government should be held to the same standards. Silencing our scientists and cutting off funds for unbiased research is not the way to go."

 

Made by Puvithel in PA. Item ships directly from vendor.
